d for more than seventy-five years. It outlines in both stark and moving detail what a cross-section of Canadians both said and did during the liberation efforts at one of the most notorious sites in Hitler’s camp system. In addition, biographical overviews are presented for each Canadian featured in the book, not only highlighting some of their life-saving and humanitarian work, but also revealing what ultimately became of their lives after the war. Kingdom of Night depicts the gruelling efforts by those who assisted the victims of one of the greatest crimes in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narratives, Canadian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campsxLiberationzGermany. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz.  aBergen-Belsen concentration camp.  aCanada.  aCanadian military history.  aHitler.  aHolocaust.  aJewish history.  aNazi Germany.  aSecond World War.  aextermination camps.  afirst-hand accounts.  aliberation.  atrauma.1 aPodemski, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107392200 cprintz978148750574540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753258140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487532581423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487532581/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles